nteraction between the diabetic syndrome, the genetic background of the patient, and the environment, DIABETES CARE 4. -561-572, SEPTEMBER-OCTOBER i98i. A n association between hyperlipidemia and dia-betic ketoacidosis was first demonstrated by Bloor in 1916. 1 It has since been appreciated that blood lipids are fairly commonly elevated among ambulant diabetic patients. 2 " 6 In view of the predisposition for the development of atherosclerotic vascular disease in the diabetic, attention has been focused on lipid and lipoprotein levels and metabolism in diabetes. This review provides a pathophysiologic approach to the lipid abnormalities in dia-betes, and will stress the important metabolic differences be-tween type I (insulin-dependent) and type II (non-insulin-dependent) diabetes. LIPID AND LIPOPROTEIN METABOLISM (FIGURE{\_}O},
